06831nam a22012015i 9780814762547DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20092009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147625477 a10.18574/nyu/9780814762172.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)548391  a(OCoLC)549609161  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aKF9227.C2bR63 2016 7aLAW0360002bisacsh04a364.66097322304aThe Road to Abolition? :bThe Future of Capital Punishment in the United States /ced. by Charles J. Ogletree Jr., Austin Sarat. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Charles Hamilton Houston Institute Series on Race and Justice ;v500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Assessing the Prospects for Abolition -- t1. The Executioner’s Waning Defenses -- t2. Blinded by Science on the Road to Abolition? -- t3. Abolition in the United States by 2050 On Political Capital and Ordinary Acts of Resistance -- t4. The Beginning of the End? -- t5. Rocked but Still Rolling -- tPart II. Debating Lethal Injection -- t6. For Execution Methods Challenges, the Road to Abolition Is Paved with Paradox -- t7. Perfect Execution -- t8. “No Improvement over Electrocution or Even a Bullet” -- tPart III. Putting the Death Penalty in Context -- t9. Torture, War, and Capital Punishment -- t10. Making Difference -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the start of the twenty-first century, America is in the midst of a profound national reconsideration of the death penalty. There has been a dramatic decline in the number of people being sentenced to death as well as executed, exonerations have become common, and the number of states abolishing the death penalty is on the rise. The essays featured in The Road to Abolition? track this shift in attitudes toward capital punishment, and consider whether or not the death penalty will ever be abolished in America.The interdisciplinary group of experts gathered by Charles J. Ogletree Jr., and Austin Sarat ask and attempt to answer the hard questions that need to be addressed if the death penalty is to be abolished. Will the death penalty end only to be replaced with life in prison without parole? Will life without the possibility of parole become, in essence, the new death penalty? For abolitionists, might that be a pyrrhic victory? The contributors discuss how the death penalty might be abolished, with particular emphasis on the current debate over lethal injection as a case study on why and how the elimination of certain forms of execution might provide a model for the larger abolition of the death penalty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCapital punishmentzUnited States. 7aLAW / Ethics & Professional Responsibility.2bisacsh  aabolished.  aabolition.  acase.  acertain.  acontributors.  acurrent.  adeath.  adebate.  adiscuss.  aelimination.  aemphasis.  aexecution.  aforms.  ainjection.  alarger.  alethal.  amight.  amodel.  aover.  aparticular.  apenalty.  aprovide.  astudy.  awith.1 aAronson, Jay D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCole, Simon A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDenno, Deborah W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitzpatrick, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarcourt, Bernard E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, David T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaufman-Osborn, Timothy V.,